<br>
Argentina is a step closer to accepting spent nuclear fuel from the new Sydney research reactor, after a political committee voted in favour of the plan. <br>
<br>
It has taken almost a year, but overnight the foreign affairs committee of the Argentine Congress voted in favour of accepting Australian spent nuclear fuel. <br>
<br>
By a margin of two to one, the committee approved the nuclear treaty with Australia that has been stalled since last November. <br>
<br>
The decision paves the way for a final vote in the coming weeks by the 256-member Chamber of Deputies. <br>
<br>
If passed, the treaty will allow the Australian Government to ask Argentina to oversee treatment of spent fuel from the new reactor, before waste is returned to Australia for long-term storage. <br>
<br>
An Argentine state-owned company won the $300 million research reactor contract.<br>
<br>
*******************************************************************************************<br>
<br>
I have high hopes that Australia will change it's policies toward nuclear power generation and become a major part of the nuclear renaissance. We are an arid nation currently suffering from our worst drought in decades. Talk of turning rivers inland and other extreme ideas are now being taken seriously. I'm hoping the Government eventually caves in to public pressure to meet global greenhouse gas emmision standards and takes effective measures to break the drought with nuclear technology. <br>
Australia is one of the richest sources of Uranium. Nuclear plants would create the electricity necessary to power large desalination facilities. Pumping large volumes of treated sea water to desperate farming regions. <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm20.showMessage?topicID=133.topic">Nuclear-Powered Weather.</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
<br>
If placed inland the nuclear-generated heat might be used to produce low-pressure regions that could pull moist air from oceans into desert areas to support agriculture. <br>
